  "doc_id": "56803",
  "text": "The application of a constant force in single-molecule force spectroscopy is now experimentally possible and has been recently applied to study protein unfolding [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The application of a constant pulling force in simulation is straightforward and has been previously used to simulate forced unbinding ) and unfolding [CITATION_3] . In a CFMD simulation, the relaxation from the initial bound conformation to the equilibrium one, where ligand and antibody are at infinite distance, is monitored. The presence of a constant force has the effect of lowering the free energy barrier for the unbinding; the thermally activated crossing of the barriers can thus be observed over shorter time scales. To explore the effect of the magnitude of the force on the unbinding mechanism, three different forces (300, 350, and 400 pN) were used in the CFMD simulations. The magnitude of the force was chosen so that, with the smallest force (300 pN), unbinding still occurred on a time scale shorter than 15 nsec. All simulations were continued until unbinding occurred.",
